    {
        "id": 20, "title": "Crackme Basics",
        "description": "Crackmes are programs that require finding a password or serial number. The goal: find the correct input that makes the program print 'Success!' without knowing the intended algorithm.",
        "challenge": "Reverse engineer this crackme logic and find the correct password:\nThe program does: key = sum(ord(c) for c in input) XOR 0xDEAD\nIt accepts if key == 0xBEEF\nWrite solve_crackme() -> str that returns a valid password.",
        "hint": "Target XOR value = 0xBEEF XOR 0xDEAD = ? . Need a string whose ASCII sum equals that value. Simple: use a single character chr(target_sum) if printable, or split across multiple chars.",
        "solution": "def solve_crackme():\n    target_key = 0xBEEF\n    xor_mask = 0xDEAD\n    target_sum = target_key ^ xor_mask\n    # Build a password whose ASCII sum == target_sum\n    # Use 'A' (65) repeated + one adjustment char\n    char_a = ord('A')\n    num_a = target_sum // char_a\n    remainder = target_sum - num_a * char_a\n    if 0x20 <= remainder < 0x7f:\n        password = 'A' * num_a + chr(remainder)\n    else:\n        # Build from printable chars\n        password = ''\n        remaining = target_sum\n        while remaining >= 0x20:\n            c = min(remaining, 0x7e)\n            password += chr(c)\n            remaining -= c\n    return password\n\ndef verify_crackme(password):\n    key = sum(ord(c) for c in password) ^ 0xDEAD\n    return key == 0xBEEF",
        "test_code": "password = solve_crackme()\nassert verify_crackme(password), f'Password {repr(password)} is incorrect'\nassert isinstance(password, str)\nassert len(password) > 0",
        "explanation": "Real crackme techniques: set a breakpoint on strcmp/memcmp to see compared values; trace backward from 'Access Denied' to the comparison; use angr (symbolic execution) to automatically find satisfying inputs.",
        "points": 25, "category": "fundamentals",
    },

