    {
        "id": 76, "title": "Exploitation Chain — Full Stack",
        "description": "Real exploits combine multiple techniques: info leak → ASLR bypass → canary bypass → ROP chain → shellcode. This challenge simulates building a complete exploit chain.",
        "challenge": "Write build_exploit_chain(target_info: dict) -> dict.\nTarget info includes: protections, vulnerabilities found, available gadgets.\nReturn: {'chain_steps': list, 'required_primitives': list, 'estimated_reliability': float}",
        "hint": "Plan: (1) info leak to defeat ASLR, (2) calculate offsets, (3) craft payload with correct canary, (4) ROP chain for shellcode/system(), (5) trigger.",
        "solution": "def build_exploit_chain(target_info):\n    protections = target_info.get('protections', [])\n    vulns = target_info.get('vulnerabilities', [])\n    gadgets = target_info.get('gadgets', [])\n    chain_steps = []\n    required_primitives = []\n    reliability = 1.0\n    # Step 1: Handle ASLR\n    if 'ASLR' in protections:\n        if 'format_string' in vulns or 'info_leak' in vulns:\n            chain_steps.append('Step 1: Use format string/info leak to leak libc/stack address')\n            chain_steps.append('Step 2: Calculate ASLR base offsets from leaked address')\n            required_primitives.append('info_leak')\n            reliability *= 0.9\n        else:\n            chain_steps.append('Step 1: ASLR present but no info leak — bruteforce or partial overwrite')\n            reliability *= 0.3\n    # Step 2: Handle Canary\n    if 'Stack Canary' in protections:\n        if 'format_string' in vulns:\n            chain_steps.append('Step 3: Use format string to leak stack canary value')\n            required_primitives.append('canary_leak')\n        else:\n            chain_steps.append('Step 3: Canary present, no leak — brute force (fork server) or skip')\n            reliability *= 0.5\n    # Step 3: Exploit primitive\n    if 'buffer_overflow' in vulns:\n        chain_steps.append('Step 4: Buffer overflow to overwrite saved RIP with ROP chain')\n        required_primitives.append('stack_overflow')\n    # Step 4: Handle NX\n    if 'NX' in protections:\n        if 'pop_rdi' in gadgets and 'system@libc' in gadgets:\n            chain_steps.append('Step 5: ROP chain: pop rdi → /bin/sh; ret → system()')\n        elif 'mprotect@plt' in gadgets:\n            chain_steps.append('Step 5: ROP chain: mprotect(stack, RWX) → execute shellcode')\n        else:\n            chain_steps.append('Step 5: No suitable ROP gadgets — one_gadget or ret2dl-resolve')\n            reliability *= 0.7\n    else:\n        chain_steps.append('Step 5: NX disabled — jump directly to shellcode on stack')\n    chain_steps.append('Step 6: Trigger exploit → shell')\n    return {'chain_steps': chain_steps, 'required_primitives': required_primitives,\n            'estimated_reliability': round(reliability, 2)}",
        "test_code": "target = {\n    'protections': ['ASLR', 'NX', 'Stack Canary'],\n    'vulnerabilities': ['buffer_overflow', 'format_string', 'info_leak'],\n    'gadgets': ['pop_rdi', 'ret', 'system@libc'],\n}\nresult = build_exploit_chain(target)\nassert len(result['chain_steps']) >= 4\nassert 'info_leak' in result['required_primitives']\nassert result['estimated_reliability'] > 0.0\nassert result['estimated_reliability'] <= 1.0",
        "explanation": "CTF pwn methodology: checksec → identify protections, pwndbg → find offsets, ROPgadget → find gadgets, pwntools → script the exploit. Real-world: add reliability techniques (heap feng shui, timing), error handling. Bug bounties pay $5k-$1M+ for browser/kernel exploits.",
        "points": 50, "category": "exploitation",
    },

